Random walk in 1d

In [ ]:
In [1]:
'''Random walk in 1D
Body is initially resting at x = 0 and it will move
either in postive or negative x direction
'''


import random

def random_walk(n):

    x = 0
    # particle postioned at x = 0
    for i in range(n):
        step = random.choice([-1,1])
        # steps being randomly assigned either +ve or -ve

        if step == -1:
            x = x-1
        else:
            x = x+1
    return (x)


number_of_walk = 300000
walk_length = 10
position = []
# length of walk defines how much steps can body take

for i in range(number_of_walk):
    walk = random_walk(walk_length)
#     (walk, "Distance from origin = ", abs(walk))
    position.append(walk)

print(f'\nWalk length = 20, total walk = 300000\n\n Positions:\n {position}')

In [11]:
'''Random walk in 1D
Body is initially resting at x = 0 and it will move
either in postive or negative x direction
'''


import random

def random_walk(n):

    x = 0
    # particle postioned at x = 0
    for i in range(n):
        step = random.choice([-1,1])
        # steps being randomly assigned either +ve or -ve

        if step == -1:
            x = x-1
        else:
            x = x+1
    return (x)


number_of_walk = int(300000)
walk_length = int(10)

position_final = []
position_n_time = []
Pos_timestamp = []

# length of walk defines how much steps can body take

for i in range(number_of_walk):
    for j in range(walk_length):
        walk = random_walk(j)
        position_n_time.append(walk)
        
    position_final.append(walk)
